    Creating

    The primary goal of exoatlas is to create populations of exoplanets which which we can interact in fairly standardized way. Here we summarize a few different pre-defined Population objects we can create.

    In[1]:
    Copied! 
    import exoatlas as ea
import astropy.units as u 

ea.version()
    import exoatlas as ea import astropy.units as u ea.version()
    Out[1]:
    '0.5.0'

    PredefinedPopulation = commonly useful archival datasets

    The atlas contains a few predefined populations, for which data are automatically downloaded from archives and standardized into tables in exoatlas's preferred format. This downloading and standardizing can take a while, so the results will be stored locally, in a directory you can locate with:

    In[2]:
    Copied! 
    ea.locate_local_data()
    ea.locate_local_data()
     `exoatlas` archive data will be stored in:
/Users/zach/exoatlas-data

    If you ever want to reset the local data, you do so either with reset_local_data() (remove all local files) or reset_standardized_data() (remove standardized files but keep raw downloads). If you have recently updated your local version of exoatlas, or

    Throughout this page we'll use handy physical_summary() wrapper as a way to visualize some of the basic properties of a particular population. For more on useful plots and plotting tools, see Visualizing.

    SolarSystem = major Solar System planets

    The eight planets in our own Solar System are useful as a comparison sample. Their properties are built-in with exoatlas, so they don't need to be downloaded from any archive.

    In[3]:
    Copied! 
    solar = ea.SolarSystem()
solar
    solar = ea.SolarSystem() solar
      [solarsystem] Loaded standardized table from /Users/zach/exoatlas-data/data/standardized-SolarSystem.txt
    Out[3]:
     Solar System | 8 elements
    In[4]:
    Copied! 
    ea.physical_summary(solar);
    ea.physical_summary(solar);

    Likewise, we have the dwarf planets, smaller minor planets, and moons:

    In[5]:
    Copied! 
    dwarfs = ea.SolarSystemDwarfPlanets()
dwarfs
    dwarfs = ea.SolarSystemDwarfPlanets() dwarfs
    [solarsystemdwarfplanets] Loaded standardized table from /Users/zach/exoatlas-data/data/standardized-SolarSystemDwarfPlanets.txt
    Out[5]:
     Solar System Dwarf Planets | 5 elements
    In[6]:
    Copied! 
    minor = ea.SolarSystemMinorPlanets()
minor
    minor = ea.SolarSystemMinorPlanets() minor
    [solarsystemminorplanets] Loaded standardized table from /Users/zach/exoatlas-data/data/standardized-SolarSystemMinorPlanets.txt
    Out[6]:
     Solar System Minor Planets | 240 elements
    In[7]:
    Copied! 
    moons = ea.SolarSystemMoons()
moons
    moons = ea.SolarSystemMoons() moons
    [solarsystemmoons] Loaded standardized table from /Users/zach/exoatlas-data/data/standardized-SolarSystemMoons.txt
    Out[7]:
     Solar System Moons | 41 elements

    Exoplanets = confirmed, published, exoplanets

    The NASA Exoplanet Archive maintains a list of confirmed transiting exoplanets. These are systems that have been published in the peer-reviewed literature. Most of them have been characterized in sufficient detail that they are unlikely to be false positives.

    This archive contains planets discovered through a variety of methods. We can access all exoplanets in the archive, regardless of discovery method, with:

    In[8]:
    Copied! 
    exoplanets = ea.Exoplanets()
exoplanets
    exoplanets = ea.Exoplanets() exoplanets
       [exoplanets] Loaded standardized table from /Users/zach/exoatlas-data/data/standardized-Exoplanets.txt
    Out[8]:
     Exoplanets | 5819 elements

    For many purposes, it will be really handy to have just those exoplanets that transit their stars. To access those:

    In[9]:
    Copied! 
    transiting = ea.TransitingExoplanets()
transiting
    transiting = ea.TransitingExoplanets() transiting
    [transitingexoplanets] Loaded standardized table from /Users/zach/exoatlas-data/data/standardized-Exoplanets.txt
    Out[9]:
     Transiting Exoplanets | 4382 elements
    In[10]:
    Copied! 
    ea.physical_summary(transiting);
    ea.physical_summary(transiting);

    Kepler vs. Non-Kepler

    Which planets were discovered by Kepler or not?

    Copied!

kepler
    kepler = ea.Kepler() kepler
           [kepler] Loaded standardized table from /Users/zach/exoatlas-data/data/standardized-Exoplanets.txt
    Out[11]:
     Kepler | 3304 elements
    In[12]:
    Copied! 
    nonkepler = ea.NonKepler()
nonkepler
    nonkepler = ea.NonKepler() nonkepler
        [nonkepler] Loaded standardized table from /Users/zach/exoatlas-data/data/standardized-Exoplanets.txt
    Out[12]:
     Non-Kepler | 1078 elements
    In[13]:
    Copied! 
    ea.physical_summary([kepler, nonkepler]);
    ea.physical_summary([kepler, nonkepler]);

    Good vs Bad Mass?

    Which planets have masses that have been detected at better than $2.5\sigma$?

    In[20]:
    Copied! 
    good = ea.GoodMass(sigma=2.5)
good
    good = ea.GoodMass(sigma=2.5) good
         [goodmass] Loaded standardized table from /Users/zach/exoatlas-data/data/standardized-Exoplanets.txt
    Out[20]:
     Good Mass | 1129 elements
    In[21]:
    Copied! 
    bad = ea.BadMass(sigma=2.5)
bad
    bad = ea.BadMass(sigma=2.5) bad
          [badmass] Loaded standardized table from /Users/zach/exoatlas-data/data/standardized-Exoplanets.txt
    Out[21]:
     Bad Mass | 3253 elements
    In[22]:
    Copied! 
    ea.physical_summary([bad, good]);
    ea.physical_summary([bad, good]);

    From all these basic populations, you can make your own to play with by indexing, slicing, or masking as described in Exploring. Have fun!
